AB  - The N cycles for a red pine Pinus resinosa plantation and a mixed hardwood stand in central Massachusetts, both of which were found to have high 'resistance' to nutrient losses following disturbance, are presented. Both stands exhibit 1) slow rates of N cycling, 2) undetectable levels of nitrate and ammonia in lysimeter samples collected below the rooting zone, 3) small to negligible enrichment of N in throughfall compared with stemflow, and 4) no immobilization of N in decomposing leaf litter. All of these indicate a slow and tight N cycle and may also be indicative of 'resistant' systems. Four major sinks for N within disturbed plots (created by trenching around a 1 X 4 m soil block) are analysed; 1) denitrification, 2) leaching losses below the rooting zone and immobilization into 3) fine roots and 4) woody roots. In the hardwood stand these account for only 37 of 104 kg N ha-1 mineralized and 66 of 90 kg N ha-1 in the pines. An additional internal sink may be a delayed immobilization potential resulting from the lack of immobilization in decomposing leaf litter. This creates soil organic matter which may be used as a substrate for further immobilization when the removal of plant uptake increases N availability in soils. Additional immobilization may result from a switch from a decomposition system dominated by symbiotic mycorrhizal fungi to one dominated by free-living microbes.-Authors
