AB  - A mycorrhiza is an association between soil fungus and a plant root and most vascular plants form mycorrhizal associations where the fungus benefits from photosynthetically derived carbon compounds. It has been known that mycorrhizas enhance uptake of mineral nutrients, particularly of phosphorus. Research has demonstrated that mycorrhizas also play an important role in the uptake of nutrients from organic materials. Ericoid mycorrhizas and some ectomycorrhizas (EM) species have the potential to degrade structural compounds of plant litter and mobilize nitrogen and phosphorus directly from organic polymers so that they are able to short circuit the microbial mineralization process. The role of mycorrhizas in the distribution of forest species is observed in New Zealand indigenous forests. All of the tree species that spread as wildings of any consequence in the country form ectomycorrhizas.
