AB  - Isotopes of nitrogen (delta N-15) and carbon (delta C-13) in ectomycorrhizal and saprotrophic fungi contain important information about ecological functioning, but the complexity of physiological and ecosystem processes contributing to fungal carbon and nitrogen dynamics has limited our ability to explain differences across taxa. Here, we measured delta N-15 and delta C-13 in needles, litter, soil, wood, fungal caps, and fungal stipes at numerous forested sites in Oregon, USA to determine how functional attributes and biochemical processes may influence isotopic values. Ectomycorrhizal fungi were classified by hydrophobicity of ectomycorrhizae and by patterns of hyphal exploration: saprotrophic fungi were classified into wood decay and litter decay fungi. For delta N-15, caps of hydrophobic taxa averaged 8.6 parts per thousand, hydrophilic taxa 3.2 parts per thousand and saprotrophic taxa 0.5 parts per thousand, whereas needles averaged 3 parts per thousand and soil at 5-12 cm averaged 2 parts per thousand. Caps were higher in delta N-15, delta C-13, \%N, and \%C than stipes by 1.7 parts per thousand, 0.6 parts per thousand 1.75\%, and 2.61\%, respectively, presumably because of greater protein content in caps than stipes. Isotopic enrichment of caps relative to stipes was greater in hydrophobic taxa (3.1 parts per thousand for N-15 and 0.8 parts per thousand, for C-13) than in hydrophilic taxa (1.1 parts per thousand for N-15 and 0.5 parts per thousand for C-13). In multiple regressions, 45\% of variance in delta N-15(cap-stipe) and 30\% of variance in delta C-13(cap-stipe) was accounted for by various elemental, isotopic, and categorical variables. We estimated that fungal protein was enriched in N-15 relative to fungal chitin by 15 parts per thousand in hydrophobic taxa and by 7 parts per thousand in hydrophilic taxa. Fungal protein was enriched in C-13 by 4.2 +/- 0.5 parts per thousand relative to carbohydrates. Isotopic signatures of sources and isotopic fractionation during metabolic processing influence both isotopic patterns of sporocarps and the isotopic partitioning between caps and stipes; functional groups differed in processing of both nitrogen isotopes and carbon isotopes. (C) 2012 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.
