AB  - Reviews the major biogeochemical inputs and pathways in Australian rain forest ecosystems, indicating the significance of rainfall and dust decomposition, nitrogen fixation and rock weathering. Major biogeochemical losses occur as a result of surface runoff which transports topsoil and leaf litter into streams, and through denitrification. Major nutrient exchanges occur as a result of throughfall and stemflow, litterfall, litter decomposition and nutrient incorporation into plant biomass. Nutrient conserving mechanisms include translocation of nutrients, foliar uptake, uptake by tree and leaf epiphytes, development of aerial roots, large root masses and the presence of mycorrhizal hyphae close to or amongst decomposing litter. Logging, storms, forest clearing and burning can also affect nutrient cycling. The introduction of an entirely new community of species which can tolerate impoverished soil may be necessary to re-establish the biomass nutrient pools and nutrient cycles. -S.J.Yates
