AB  - There are many alterations in the composition and development of plants on Camels Hump Mountain. Simulation studies show that acidic, metal-containing precipitations are capable of causing alterations in the growth and metabolism of components of these ecosystems. It is alterations to determine how far the laboratory data can be extrapolated to relate it to the data obtained in the field. The decline and death of red spruce, the reduction in moss coverage, the increase in litter depth, the accumulation and solubilization of metals in the soils, the absence of mycorrhiza on spruce roots and other alterations noted since the initial ecological study suggest strongly that the forests of Camels Hump are reacting to severe stresses. Studies indicate that disease or insect infestations are not involved. Acid rain is a reasonable candidate as a major perturbing influence, but the evidence is still inadequate to make a firm probability statement.
